HASH MAPS

=> Although arrays offer random access, they have fixed size.
=> Although linked lists are of dynamic size, random access is not possible.
=> Hashmaps offer both random access and are of dynamic size.

=> A key is input to a hash function to derive a hash value. The value corresponding to the key is mapped to this hash value in the hash table.
=> The hash function should be built in a way that there are fewer collisions (same hash value for multiple keys).
=> Collisions can be resolved through linear probing (alloting next available slot leading to clustering) or separate chaining (linked list, O(n/k) better than O(n) in real world)
=> Although there are mechanisms to handle collisions, it would be best to avoid collisions in the first place. For this the hash function should be developed such that collisions do not occur frequently.
